The paper proposes an algorithm for Non-negative Matrix Factorisation (NMF) that considers pairwise relationships among rows or columns, which is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. Specifically, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is the most likely category as NMF is a popular technique in this field. cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is also relevant as NMF has been used in recommender systems, which is mentioned in the abstract. cs.CV (Computer Vision) is another possible category as NMF has been used in image clustering, which is also mentioned in the abstract. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is relevant as the paper discusses the convergence of the algorithm and the use of approximations to relax the complexity brought by the penalties. Finally, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is relevant as NMF has been used in network analysis, which is related to pairwise relationships among features.
